hands_on_practices.solution:
We wish to find 
$$T=\int_0^L\frac{dx}{u(x)},$$ 
where in the lab frame the light‐speed in the medium moving at $v(x)=\alpha x$ is by relativistic addition
$$u(x)=\frac{c/n + v(x)}{1+\frac{(c/n)\,v(x)}{c^2}}
=\frac{\frac{c}{n}+\alpha x}{1+\frac{\alpha x}{n c}}.$$
Thus
$$\frac1{u(x)}
=\frac{1+\frac{\alpha x}{n c}}{\frac{c}{n}+\alpha x}
=\frac{n c+\alpha x}{c^2+n c\,\alpha x},$$
and
$$T=\int_0^L\frac{n c+\alpha x}{c^2+n c\,\alpha x}\,dx
=\int_0^L\frac{n c}{c^2+n c\,\alpha x}\,dx
+\int_0^L\frac{\alpha x}{c^2+n c\,\alpha x}\,dx.$$

1.  First integral:
$$I_1=\int_0^L\frac{n c}{c^2+n c\,\alpha x}\,dx
=\frac{n c}{n c\,\alpha}\int_{c^2}^{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}\frac{du}{u}
=\frac1\alpha\ln\frac{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}{c^2}.$$

2.  Second integral: set $u=c^2+n c\,\alpha x$, $du=n c\,\alpha\,dx$, $x=(u-c^2)/(n c\,\alpha)$:
$$I_2=\int_{u=c^2}^{u=c^2+n c\,\alpha L}
\frac{\alpha\,(u-c^2)}{n c\,\alpha}\,\frac{du}{u}
=\frac1{n c}\int_{c^2}^{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}\Bigl(1-\frac{c^2}{u}\Bigr)\,du.$$
Hence
$$I_2
=\frac1{n c}\Bigl[u-c^2\ln u\Bigr]_{c^2}^{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}
=\frac{n c\,\alpha L}{n c}-\frac{1}{n c}\,c^2\ln\frac{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}{c^2}
=\frac{L}{n c}-\frac1{n^2\alpha}\ln\frac{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}{c^2}.$$

Adding $I_1+I_2$ gives
$$T=\frac{L}{n c}
+\Bigl(\frac1\alpha-\frac1{n^2\alpha}\Bigr)\ln\frac{c^2+n c\,\alpha L}{c^2}
=\frac{L}{n c}+\frac{n^2-1}{n^2\alpha}\ln\!\Bigl(1+\frac{n\alpha L}{c}\Bigr).$$
